#Load Package(s)
from plotnine import *

#assign axis values
xbreak_values = [500, 1000, 2000, 4000, 8000, 16000, 32000, 64000]
xlabel_values = [500, 1000, 2000, 4000, 8000, '16k', '32k', '64k']
ybreak_values = [20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90]

#Assign fill colors for regions
p1fill_colors = {
    'africa': 'cyan',
    'americas': 'lime',
    'asia': 'r',
    'europe': 'yellow',
}
    
#Construct Plot
plot1 = (
ggplot(q1data,aes("income","life_exp",fill = "four_regions", size="population")) 
+ annotate("text", x=8000, y=52, label="2010",color="grey",size=150,alpha=0.2)
+ annotate("text", x=1400, y=90, label="INCOME LEVEL 1",color="silver",size=8)
+ annotate("text", x=5000, y=90, label="LEVEL 2",color="silver",size=8)
+ annotate("text", x=14600, y=90, label="LEVEL 3",color="silver",size=8)
+ annotate("text", x=46000, y=90, label="LEVEL 4",color="silver",size=8)
+ annotate("text", x=42000, y=20, label="per person(GDP/capita,PPPS inflation-adjusted)",color="silver",size=6)
+ geom_point(alpha=0.97) 
+ scale_size([0.5,19])
+ scale_fill_manual(values=p1fill_colors)
+ labs(x='Income',y='Life Expectancy') 
+ scale_x_continuous(breaks=xbreak_values,labels = xlabel_values, trans = 'log2')
+ scale_y_continuous(limits = [20,90], breaks = [20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90])
+ theme_light()
+ theme_bw()
+ theme(figure_size=(9, 5))
      )
#View Plot
plot1

<Figure Size: (900 x 500)>

  1. What other geometries could you use here besides geom_point? Provide an actual plot of another geometry being used here and why itâs good or bad for visualizing these data.

    Another geometry you could use is geom_boxplot which is not as effective for visualizing the data. It is not as effective because the boxplot geometry does not distuinguish the various countries within the four regions as well as the scatter/bubble plot. One bonus of geom_boxplot is that it better represents the quartiles for each region, however, the individual countries are not represented.


plot1b = (ggplot(q1data,aes("income","life_exp", fill = "four_regions", size = "population"))
+ geom_boxplot()
         )

  1. Recreate the plot as best you can using plotnine.
#Load Package(s)
from plotnine import *
from pandas import to_numeric
#Assign fill colors for regions
p2fill_colors = {
    'africa': 'cyan',
    'americas': 'lime',
    'asia': 'r',
    'europe': 'yellow',
}

#Change energy to a numeric variable
q2data["energy"] = to_numeric(q2data["energy"])

#Construct Plot
plot2 = (
ggplot(q2data,aes("exports","imports",fill = "four_regions", size = "energy"))
+ annotate("text", x=110, y=200, label="1997",color="grey",size=150,alpha=0.2)
+ geom_point(alpha=0.97) 
+ scale_size([0.5,18])
+ scale_fill_manual(values=p2fill_colors)
+ labs(x='Exports (/% of GDP)',y='Imports (/% of GDP)') 
+ scale_x_continuous(limits = [0,220], breaks = [20, 40, 60, 80, 100, 120, 140, 160, 180, 200, 220])
+ scale_y_continuous(limits = [0,400], breaks = [50, 100, 150, 200, 250, 300, 350, 400])
+ theme_light()
+ theme_bw()
+ theme(figure_size=(9, 5))
      )
#View Plot
plot2

    Other geometries you could use involve geom_violin which is not as effective for visualizing the data. It is not as effective because the violin geometry does not distinguish the various countries like the boxplot geometry, and also requires non overlapping x-intervals which does not comply with the data.

    'americas': 'lime',
    'asia': 'r',
    'europe': 'yellow',

                     labels = [200, 500, 1000, 2000, 5000, '10k', '20k', '50k', '100k'],
                     trans = 'log2')
+ theme_light()
+ theme_bw()

  1. What other geometries could you use here besides geom_point? Provide an actual plot of another geometry being used here and why itâs good or bad for visualizing these data.

    Another geometry that you could use (other than geom_boxplot and geom_violin) is geom_point. This geometry provides a very ugly and ineffective visualization of the data because the lines between the various countries within each region are unnecessary. This does provide a distinction between the various countries in the region, however, unlike the boxplot and violin geometries.

plot3b = (
ggplot(q3data,aes("internet_users","gdp",fill = "four_regions", size = "income"))
+ geom_line()
+ geom_point()
)
plot3b
